Title: Visualised coordination support in distributed decision making  
Author: Peter Svenmarck 
Affiliation: Division of Industrial Ergonomics Linkping Institute of Technology  
Abstract: This paper is concerned with support of the communication of intentions, as this information is important for individuals coordinating locally. A visual communication of intentions was attempted by visualising the behaviour of actors on a dynamic blackboard shown to all. The experiment was inspired by results in social perception, where subjects perceived intentions directly from body movement. The blackboard was implemented in D 3 FIRE, a general paradigm for studying distributed decision making where a group of four subjects are charged with the task of fighting a simulated forest fire, and compared with individuals only communicating by electronic written messages. Contrary to expectations performance decreased with the blackboard. There is, however, a significant decrease in the frequency of communicated intentions since this information was present on the blackboard. Some possible explanations are discussed. First, the design of the blackboard where the location of the units is always visible might explain the reduction in communication of important information about the progress of the fire fighting and this could result in a overconfidence of the control of the fire. Second, only behaviour could be insufficient for visualising the processing involved in fire fighting. More factors such as the wind direction and the location of the fire fighting units in relation to the fire could be required for a unambiguous perception of what the subjects are doing. 
