Reference-contexts: Some mean of communicating intentions is probably important for a successful local coordination. In the experiment by Brehmer and Svenmarck (1995), intentions were communicated verbally with electronic messages. This form of communication is, however, sensitive to time pressure <ref> (Serfaty, et al., 1994) </ref>, and mental load, and it is therefor important to consider other nonverbal modes of communication. Results by Runeson and Frykholm (1983) indicate such an alternative where only a minimum amount of information about a persons movement was sufficient for direct perception of the persons intention. <p> This is the idea with implicit coordination. When time pressure is high, coordination is more implicit and based on prediction of the others behaviour from knowledge about their situation <ref> (Serfaty, et al., 1994) </ref>. There are some serious difficulties with this form of coordination. To succeed in predicting the behaviour, the subject must know the others model of the task and the situation they currently face, and this is normally very difficult in a dynamic task with limited communication resources.
